{
  "id": "matrix-chain-order",
  "title": "Matrix Chain Multiplication",
  "difficulty": "MEDIUM",
  "statement": "You need to multiply a chain of matrices. Matrix `i` has dimensions `dims[i-1] \u00d7 dims[i]`. The cost of multiplying an `a\u00d7b` matrix by a `b\u00d7c` matrix is `a\u00d7b\u00d7c`. Find the **minimum total cost** to multiply all matrices in the chain.\n\n**Input:** Space-separated dimensions array (length = number of matrices + 1).\n**Output:** Minimum multiplication cost.",
  "constraints": "- 2 \u2264 dims.length \u2264 500\n- 1 \u2264 dims[i] \u2264 500",
  "examples": [
    {
      "input": "40 20 30 10 30",
      "output": "26000",
      "explanation": "Optimal parenthesization gives 26000 operations."
    },
    {
      "input": "10 30 5 60",
      "output": "4500",
      "explanation": "Multiply (A\u00d7B)\u00d7C: (10\u00d730\u00d75)+(10\u00d75\u00d760)=1500+3000=4500."
    },
    {
      "input": "1 2 3 4",
      "output": "18",
      "explanation": "Multiply (A\u00d7B)\u00d7C first: (1\u00d72\u00d73)+(1\u00d73\u00d74)=6+12=18."
    }
  ],
